<TEXT>
the defeat of us legislation that would have 
helped chinese students extend their stays in the united states is 
not likely to reverse chinas course of tightening exit controls 
the door already has closed significantly on what had been the 
freest period for exit from china in its 40 years of communist 
rule during which almost anyone who could get a scholarship abroad 
and a foreign visa was able to go 
regulations being circulated internally bar anyone under 30 or 
with less than five years of work experience from obtaining 
official sponsorship to study abroad sources in the education 
bureaucracy said this week 
other measures have made it harder for students to take tests 
for study abroad and obtain passports without official sponsorship 
fear of its students not returning home is only one reason for 
chinas shift in policy 
more basic is the governments fear that too many students are 
returning with antisocialist ideas that could undermine their 
hardwon communist revolution 
in september premier li peng set out the new policy 
henceforth those being sent to study abroad should mainly be 
visiting scholars and researchers because these people are older 
and more mature politically 
more than educational exchanges were at stake in the showdown 
between the us congress and president bush however 
a biting frontpage editorial friday in the party newspaper the 
peoples daily said if the legislation passed the united states 
shall be held responsible for the grave consequences 
it called the bill a naked expression of power politics and 
said its supporters were antichina addicts who hoped to coerce 
china into giving up socialism 
the bill would have waived a requirement the estimated 32000 
chinese in the united states as official exchange students return 
home for two years before seeking new us visas to work or 
continue study its goal was to protect students who feared 
retribution for protesting chinas crackdown on prodemocracy 
demonstrators in june 
both houses of congress passed the bill in november but bush 
vetoed it the house of representatives voted thursday to override 
the veto but the senates 6237 vote friday in favor of the bill 
fell four short of the necessary twothirds margin for an override 
china did not comment on the bills defeat although it was 
reported on national television and radio 
bushs veto of the bill was one of a series of conciliatory us 
steps that halted the serious deterioration in uschinese 
relations after june after the december visit of bushs national 
security adviser brent scowcroft china softened its comments on 
dissidents fang lizhi and his wife li shuxian who have been 
hiding in the us embassy in beijing since june 
however bushs success in quashing the controversial bill does 
not guarantee a speedy solution to the fangs dilemma china has 
little reason to push for a resolution which would require 
compromise on its part indications are that china continues to 
insist the fangs promise not to make political statements if they 
are allowed to go to a third country a promise that those who 
know fang believe he will not make 
moreover the strong support for the bill in congress and among 
the american public reveal ideological tensions that will prevent 
bilateral relations from returning to their rosy prejune state 
americans have been awakened to the harsher side of chinas 
communist rule and chinese leaders have stressed the need for 
vigilance against what they consider subversive american notions of 
democracy 
china wont stop sending students abroad they are vital to its 
plans for absorbing advanced technology but it will take 
strenuous measures to ensure that those who go abroad are loyal 
socialists and return that way 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
kathy wilhelm has reported for the associated 
press from beijing since 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

