<TEXT>
manuel noriega may have tried to put a curse on 
us attorney general dick thornburgh and the judge in his case 
federal prosecutors suggested friday at the deposed panamanian 
leaders bond hearing 
when invading us troops raided a noriega office now referred 
to as the witch house a room in his headquarters at fort 
amador just outside panama city they found black magic 
paraphernalia including an altar 
one soldier described signs of animal entrails and vats of 
blood as well as a portrait of adolf hitler 
on friday deputy assistant us attorney myles malman asked 
us district judge william hoeveler to deny bond to noriega 
because he was a danger to the community citing among other 
reasons a white sheet of paper with four names on it that the 
troops found with the other items in the witch house 
the list consisted of thornburgh charles sapho the head 
justice departments drug section mark schnapp a former miami 
federal prosecutor partly responsible for the noriega indictment 
and hoeveler himself 
malman did not mention a curse but such lists are sometimes put 
on altars by practitioners of voodoolike afrocaribbean religions 
to place a hex on those named 
maybe i better not enter it into evidence the judge joked 
as malman handed him the list 
hoeveler later denied bond to noriega 
</TEXT>
