<DOCNO> AP900127-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the suspended superintendent of the camp 
hill prison was fired friday for his actions during a threeday 
riot last year that left 123 people injured and more than half the 
institution in ruins 
the dismissals of superintendent robert freeman and one of his 
deputies were based on a recommendation by gov robert p casey 
who said friday that freeman was among the officials with primary 
responsibility for maintaining order 
casey concluded that those having responsibility for security 
should be held accountable for their actions 
three days of rioting at camp hill in october left 123 inmates 
officers and firefighters injured and caused an estimated 14 
million in damage administrators declared the prison secure after 
a first night of rioting oct 25 but inmates were able to free 
themselves and continued their rampage through oct 27 
on nov 1 just days after the rioting ended the associated 
press reported that guards had complained that prison officials 
ignored warnings of celllocking mechanisms being broken after the 
first night of rioting on oct 25 
freeman was suspended without pay the same day attempts to 
reach him for comment on his firing were unsuccessful because his 
telephone number is unlisted 
also fired was camp hills deputy for operations robert smith 
said corrections department spokesman kenneth robinson the 
spokesman said the dismissals were ordered by state prison 
commissioner david s owens jr on the governors recommendation 
terry henry camp hills deputy for treatment will be 
reassigned within the department robinson said the governor said 
he would have recommended the dismissal of maj john stover 
captain of the guard but stover had resigned 
in a news release casey cited the findings of an independent 
threemember investigative commission that concluded management at 
camp hill had failed to adequately search the prison after the 
first night of rioting management also failed to assure that cells 
were locked despite warnings that they werent secure the 
commission found 
the commission which presented its report in december also 
said that supervisory personnel had failed to keep an adequate 
force of state troopers at the prison to prevent a second night of 
rioting and that ample time was available for management to 
reconsider its decisions 
the panel criticized owens the prison commissioner for his 
handsoff dealing with the riots but the governor said he had 
confidence in owens 
the commission recognized that direct and primary 
responsibility for the security at camp hill did not rest with 
him casey said i have concluded that commissioner owens 
carried out his responsibilities in a competent and professional 
manner 
robinson said acting superintendent jeffrey beard would remain 
in place at the prison 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

