<DOCNO> AP900127-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bigcity mayors disappointed with president 
bushs antidrug efforts are asking the administration and 
congress to cut defense spending and raise taxes to finance 
solutions for innercity problems 
the us conference of mayors ended its threeday winter meeting 
friday after the president urged them to support his new drug 
strategy and proposal to increase federal antinarcotics drug 
spending by 11 billion 
but the mayors had more money in mind and the groups 
policymaking executive committee adopted a resolution urging the 
immediate use of a peace dividend in conjuction with increased 
revenues for an injection of new aid for americas cities 
the bush administrations approach is to force the poor people 
to decide between heating and eating said newark nj mayor 
sharpe james a democrat i think they need both 
the resolution was proposed by madison wis mayor paul soglin 
it repeats the mayors longstanding call for more federal taxes to 
finance urban needs it adds the socalled peace dividend saying 
the lessening of world tensions and crumbling of communism in 
eastern europe should leave military money available for such 
pressing domestic needs as poverty homelessness aids and drugs 
new york mayor david dinkins in backing the proposal said 
the peace dividend is not the entire answer but it is a good 
start a mere 5 percent savings in defense spending will yield 15 
billion that could be used for muchneeded urban programs 
bush appealed to the overwhelmingly democratic conference of 
mayors one day after unveiling his revised plan for fighting drugs 
he offered the mayors no specifics and no other initiatives on 
urban problems 
he repeated his call for more private efforts pledging to use 
his bully pulpit to ask for volunteers 
lets join hands to inspire the millions of americans who want 
to help america get clean and stay clean he said together 
lets defeat public enemy no 1 
but some mayors questioned whether the administration was really 
making drugs its top priority and faulted bush for failing to 
provide enough money to make drug rehabilitation treatment 
available to any drug user who wants it 
we have not yet seen a level of commitment in line with the 
size of the problem said mayor kathyrn whitmire of houston 
president of the conference and the elected leader of bushs 
adopted hometown we have not yet seen it move to the top of the 
agenda in the federal government 
mayors interviewed after the speech said they appreciated the 
symbolic support his appearance provided but that bush had offered 
the cities little that was new 
i guess you have to give the president a b for showing up 
said boston mayor raymond l flynn a democrat 
i think there is strong disagreement as to how to proceed to 
address some of the issues of urban america that have been ignored 
for such a long period of time he said 
i like what he said about education said mayor karen vialle 
of tacoma wash but we need the bucks to do it 
whitmire however said city officials believe the bush 
administration is more receptive to the mayors than president 
reagan was reagan never addressed the conference of mayors in his 
eight years as president 
