<TEXT>
the energy department is dropping plans to 
build a plutonium refinery in idaho that the reagan administration 
had called essential to modernizing the nuclear weapons complex 
according to department sources 
the decision reflects the bush administrations reconsideration 
of nuclear arms priorities in light of democratic reforms in 
eastern europe and domestic budget pressures 
the decision to end financing for the special isotope separation 
plant planned for construction at the idaho national engineering 
laboratory near idaho falls will be part of the fiscal 1991 budget 
president bush sends to congress monday according to sources who 
spoke friday on condition of anonymity 
the plant was expected to cost at least 12 billion but 400 
million already has been spent on design and related work and 
construction has not started 
just 13 months ago in an official blueprint for modernizing the 
nuclear arms production complex the reagan administration called 
the idaho project timecritical and essential it was to have 
been the first new atomic weapon plant since the n reactor which 
produced plutonium at the hanford nuclear reservation near 
richland wash was put into operation 27 years ago 
the projects refining technology which uses lasers to vaporize 
plutonium so that it can be used in nuclear warheads has been 
criticized as unduly hazardous by environmental groups 
energy secretary james d watkins strongly backed the idaho 
project in congressional testimony early last year but has been 
reconsidering for several months 
phil hamric manager of the energy departments idaho field 
office declined to confirm the decision 
the department announced friday however that it had 
indefinitely postponed a series of public hearings that would form 
part of the foundation for a study of the environmental impact of a 
prototype for the idaho plutonium refinery 
the postponement which was not explained by the department 
apparently resulted from watkins decision to drop the idaho 
project watkins had announced last year that the department would 
prepare an environmental impact report on plutonium refining 
experiments with the prototype which is at livermore calif 
the hearings were to have been held feb 2 and 3 at livermore 
and feb 7 at idaho falls 
on wednesday sens james mcclure and steve symms republicans 
of idaho issued a joint statement saying they expected the 1991 
budget to contain no money for the project both were strong 
supporters of the project 
if what we have learned is correct it appears that there will 
be zero funding in the budget for construction of the plant the 
senators said adding that they accepted the decision based upon 
a variety of global developments and budgetary issues 
the snake river alliance a boisebased environmental group 
said they interpreted the idaho senators statement as meaning the 
project was dead 
we believe that construction funds for this porkbarrel relic 
of the cold war will never be seen in the federal budget again 
said elizabeth paul the groups executive director 
in a related development friday the energy department announced 
it was replacing the manager of the troubled rocky flats plutonium 
processing plant near denver which has been closed since november 
to review management and safety procedures 
watkins said robert m nelson jr deputy manager of the 
departments nevada field office in las vegas would take over at 
rocky flats for david p simonson who will move to the deputy 
managers slot there 
