with 12 chimes of a 500yearold bell the beat 
of a drum and a deafening roar of firecrackers beijing welcomed 
the year of the horse today 
at the stroke of midnight the citys mayor chen xitong struck 
the 500yearold bronze bell chinas largest and heaviest a 
dozen times residents set off a hail of firecrackers and fireworks 
to greet the lunar new year which in china is called spring 
festival 
each lunar year is represented by one of 12 animals of the 
chinese zodiacal calendar the year of the horse follows the year 
of the snake 
as the mayor struck the bell a worker and a soldier nearby beat 
two large red drums atop beijings drum tower but both the drums 
and the bell were drowned out by the cacophony of firecrackers that 
lasted unbroken for about 15 minutes 
the sounding of the bell and drum revived an imperial tradition 
and the official xinhua news agency said they would be sounded on 
the eve of every spring festival the bell and drum towers were 
timekeepers for imperial beijing but neither has been used for 66 
years since the last emperor left the imperial palace 
in the old society thats how we knew the time said a 
60yearold native of beijing who lives near the two towers the 
woman who did not give her name said it was the first time she 
had heard the bell or the drum since 1949 when the communists took 
power 
also at midnight premier li peng and communist party chief 
jiang zemin gave their holiday greetings on television the unusual 
appearance was part of an annual prerecorded fourhour new years 
eve variety show one of chinas mostwatched television shows 
the chinese leadership earlier this week traveled to the 
provinces to bring spring festival holiday greetings to workers and 
to thank soldiers for their role in putting down last springs 
prodemocracy movement 
during a sixday tour of shanxi province in northern china 
