707 
colombias civil aviation authority does not permit news media 
to review aircraft maintenance records but rcn indicated it spoke 
to someone with access to the records 
it gave no further details on the maintenance records such as 
what the problems were and whether any regulations had been 
violated 
the plane which had 161 people on board crashed thursday night 
in cove neck long island as it was approaching john f kennedy 
international airport in new york the flight originated in bogota 
and stopped in medellin 
avianca and airport officials have declined to comment on the 
possible cause of the accident 
some reports said the plane had lost use of an engine but 
alfredo parra a airline pilot instructor inteviewed in bogota 
said the aircraft could have continued to fly even if it lost two 
engines 
why the aircraft didnt try to land at an alternate airport 
even if one or two of its engines was inoperative is an important 
question to be asked in the investigation parra said in an 
interview with the caracol radio network 
colombian aviation experts said investigators should try to 
determine why the plane which some reports said ran out of fuel 
was circling new york instead of heading for an alternative airport 
where weather conditions were better it was raining the night of 
the crash 
a veteran avianca pilot noted the pilot had to abort his first 
landing attempt he said that when this happens and the 707 must 
gain altitude quickly without much fuel left the remaining fuel 
is forced to the back of tanks and may cause engines to shut off 
he spoke to the associated press on condition of anonymity 
