<TEXT>
pope john paul ii told 
citizens of this impoverished island nation today that there is 
no shame in being poor 
later he left for guineabissau the second country on his tour 
of africas subsaharan nations 
in a farewell speech to president aristides pereira other 
officials and hundreds of faithful the roman catholic leader said 
i know the difficult problems that cape verde like other 
countries of this region has to solve and solve urgently 
but i also know you can count on the tried and tested spirit 
of your people who hold no illusions that the fight against the 
inclement climate and adverse social conditions will be easy 
he reminded the people of this atlantic island nation of a local 
proverb there is no shame in being poor 
in his final speech friday to tens of thousands in this onetime 
slavetrading center the pontiff appealed for an end to 
discrimination and modernday slavery of all kinds 
the pontiff was on his first visit to this 10island archipelago 
about 380 miles west of senegal in west africa he is on an 
eightday tour of africas subsaharan sahel region which has long 
been plagued by drought famine and the spread of the desert 
the 45th trip of the popes 11year papacy will also take him to 
mali burkina faso and chad 
speaking at an openair mass on quebra canela beach near the 
capital cidade da praia the pontiff said the former portuguese 
colony still bore historic scars from the abominable commerce of 
human beings 
looking down from a custombuilt altar onto the crowded black 
volcanic beach john paul said his message was no to 
discrimination of any kind never slavery of man by man never 
again any form of violence that degrades human dignity 
this island nation although arid and poor appears more 
prosperous than other countries of the region thanks mainly to 
foreign aid and money sent back by thousands of islanders who live 
and work abroad 
the united states provides 6 million a year to cape verde 
making it the secondhighest recipient per capita of us foreign 
aid in africa after egypt diplomats said 
up to 700000 cape verdians nearly double the island 
population of 360000 live and work abroad mainly in the united 
states portugal france the netherlands and italy up to 400000 
are estimated to live in massachusetts and rhode island 
the islands of cape verde first prospered in the 16th century as 
a major post for the portuguese empires slave trade between africa 
and the americas with the demise of the slave trade the largely 
desolate islands slid into decline as a colony of an increasingly 
isolated empire 
cape verde gained independence from portugal in 1975 
speaking in wind and rain the pontiff also warned thousands of 
young islanders gathered at praias sports stadium against another 
form of slavery 
he cautioned against moral slavery that threatens you most 
when you are the least aware persuaded by the subtle 
influence of the latest fashion or the dominant opinion 
john paul urged youths not to follow the idols of personal 
success power riches and eroticism 
