<TEXT>
anglican archbishop lewis garnsworthy an 
outspoken cleric who tangled with political leaders over school 
funding and once scolded his own church for being too 
respectable has died he was 67 
a church spokesman said garnsworthy died in his sleep friday at 
toronto western hospital where he had been admitted last weekend 
no cause of death was given however in 1983 garnsworthy had a 
cancerous lung removed two years ago he had abdominal surgery to 
remove a tumor 
garnsworthy a tall sternfaced man with a booming voice 
tackled some of the churchs thorniest questions and often 
expressed what others left unsaid 
he constantly raised issues people had to struggle with 
said the rev elizabeth kilbourn who was ordained by garnsworthy 
to become one of denominations first women ministers he wasnt 
a wimp 
he once said a proposed union of the anglican and united 
churches had a snowballs chance in hades 
he criticized the roman catholic church for its fortress 
mentality 
he also derided his own anglican church of the 1940s as a sort 
of mascot at cocktail parties part of the respectable scene 
he once described many church services as boring and called for 
the burning of church pews and the melting down of collection 
plates 
garnsworthy who was born in edmonton studied theology at 
wycliffe college in toronto he was ordained into the priesthood in 
1946 and served in halifax before coming back to toronto 
in 1972 he took over as the ninth bishop of toronto the 
largest anglican diocese in canada he said he wanted to reach out 
to secular society 
elected archbishop of ontario in 1979 garnsworthys later 
battled then premier william davis plan to extend funds to 
catholic school on a separate basis from the public system 
garnsworthy favored one publicly funded system 
a week before the election he compared davis to adolf hitler 
for making the decision by decree the archbishop lost that 
fight but some angry conservatives later blamed him after the 1985 
provincial election ended the partys 43year dynasty in ontario 
garnsworthy who retired in 1988 is survived by his wife jean 
a son and daughter and a granddaughter 
a funeral service will be held monday at st james cathedral in 
toronto 
