a car bomb exploded near the home of 
lebanons top shiite moslem cleric today but the assassination 
attempt failed when the vehicle hit a pile of sand and blew up 
before reaching its target police said 
a police statement said an unidentified driver jumped out of the 
explosivepacked renault12 sedan as it moved into the alley toward 
a west beirut building housing the thirdfloor apartment of sheik 
mohammed mehdi shamseddin 
the car drifted to the left hit a sand rampart roadblock and 
exploded about 150 yards from the house causing no casualties or 
serious damage said the spokesman who cannot be named under 
standing rules 
shamseddin 55 is vice chairman of the higher shiite islamic 
council which leads daytoday spiritual affairs of the 12 
million shiite moslems who make up lebanons largest sect 
shamseddin took over after the councils chairman imam moussa 
sadr mysteriously disappeared in september 1978 during a visit to 
libya 
the police statement said the car was rigged with 55 pounds of 
explosives it exploded at about 630 am in the residential 
district of tallet khayat 
several cars parked in the area were damaged in the explosion 
which also shattered window glass no casualties were reported 
the sheik was at home at the time of the explosion but he was 
not hurt the statement said 
no one claimed responsibility for the car bomb by police count 
80 people were killed and 342 wounded in nine car bombings in 
lebanon last year 
security sources speaking on condition of anonymity said they 
believe the car bombing attack might be an offshoot of the power 
struggle within the shiite community between proiranian 
fundamentalists of hezbollah and the syrianbacked secular amal 
militia 
shamseddin is a moderate who sympathizes with amals chief nabih 
berri who is also minister of water and hydraulic resources in the 
government of president elias hrawi and prime minister salim hoss 
berri is locked in a war of words with former iranian interior 
minister ali akbar mohtashemi the hardliner who founded hezbollah 
when he was ambassador to syria in the early 1980s 
the police spokesman said amal and hezbollah fighters skirmished 
today with machine guns in south lebanons iqlim altuffah 
district but no casualties were reported by police count 98 
people have been killed and 286 wounded since the latest round of 
amalhezbollah clashes began in the province dec 23 
