trial begins tuesday in a unique race 
discrimination case with legal and social implications a black 
woman fired by the irs is suing her boss a darkerskinned black 
woman claiming discrimination because of color 
tracy lynn morrow would become the first black worker to collect 
damages from a black supervisor because of skinshade 
discrimination according to her attorney and federal equal 
opportunity officials 
us district judge charles moye ruled last spring that such 
light vs dark blackonblack discrimination is possible and that 
the issue should be decided in court 
ms morrow contends that she was targeted for harassment because 
of her skin tone her boss ruby lewis contends that ms morrow 
then tracy lynn walker was errorprone belligerent frequently 
late and dishonest 
ms morrow a former internal revenue service temporary employee 
in seattle was hired in atlanta as a clerktypist in 1985 she 
entered probation for a permanent position on dec 9 1985 but was 
fired on march 14 1986 
a race relations expert in atlanta charles king believes ms 
morrow will have a tough time proving discrimination because both 
sides acknowledge the position eventually was filled with another 
black woman 
the whole thing is lamentable that the courts would accept 
this as discrimination said king nationally known for his 
confrontational race relations seminars to me its interesting 
but logistically and logically theres no case 
ms morrows attorney stephen katz disagrees the judge he 
noted has already ascertained that ms morrow is a member of what 
is known in the law as a protected class now he said she 
must prove that she was improperly replaced by someone outside the 
protected class or show direct evidence of discrimination 
katz declined to discuss his evidence before trial but said he 
is confident he can prove discrimination the nonjury trial is 
expected to take about four days 
