latest motions but essentially they are the same as earlier 
requests 
one challenges the states jurisdiction in the case and another 
seeks to prohibit as evidence the results of a bloodalcohol test 
that hazelwood failed about 10 hours after the exxon valdez ran 
aground 
the hull of the tanker ripped open march 24 on a charted reef in 
prince william sound and gushed nearly 11 million gallons of alaska 
crude into the pristine waters the oil blackened shores in the 
sound and the gulf of alaska killed thousands of animals and 
disrupted commercial fishing seasons exxon says the cleanup has 
cost 2 billion 
hazelwood who was not on the bridge when the crash happened 
faces a felony charge of criminal mischief and misdemeanor charges 
of operating a vessel while intoxicated reckless endangerment and 
negligent discharge of oil 
the charges carry combined maximum penalties of seven years 
three months in prison and 61000 in fines 
defense attorney dick madson is expected to argue that hazelwood 
left sound instructions for members of the crew and cannot be held 
criminally responsible for their actions third mate gregory 
cousins was at the wheel of the 987foot tanker when it ran into 
bligh reef after leaving designated shipping lanes 
anchorage assistant district attorney brent cole would not 
discuss the prosecutions plans in the past prosecutors have said 
that hazelwood should have been at the helm since he was the ships 
only authorized navigator for prince william sound his lawyers say 
