faces familiar gossip still makes the circuit drugs sometimes 
change hands and families still struggle to get by 
this is no longer the el chorrillo neighborhood however but 
its essence distilled down by an invasion and filtered into an 
airplane hangar at albrook field a jointuse air base used by us 
and panamanian forces 
we paid the highest price for the invasion says francisco 
martinez we had little but we lost it all 
martinez is among the estimated 16000 refugees from el 
chorrillo the neighborhood with the bad luck to be the home of the 
panamanian defense forces headquarters the us armys main target 
during the invasion of panama on dec 20 
president bush on thursday proposed giving 1 billion in 
economic aid to panama and local officials said they are 
discussing plans to provide new homes for the refugees 
but despite those good intentions the refugees most likely will 
be living in tents or in small cubbyholes in a big hangar for at 
least a year 
it is unjust things ought to move a lot faster these people 
need a home said sergio galvez director of the camp sheltering 
3500 refugees on the northwestern edge of panama city 
a us civilian affairs group is working with panamanian 
officials trying to determine how to house the homeless while 
rebuilding goes on 
we can only make recommendations said vince ryan a houston 
city councilman who is a member of the group the panamanian 
government must make a decision they are talking about different 
things that could be done ranging from building apartment 
buildings giving each family credit to build a home or turning 
this area into a commercial area 
but anyone who tells you they can rebuild in nine months is an 
optimist said ryan 
families live in partitions made of wooden frames and canvas 
some of the alleys have been given names of streets from the old 
neighborhood less than two miles away 
no gossips allowed reads a piece of canvas that serves as a 
door on one of the partitions 
gossip and disinformation are some of the problems said 
galvez people get desperate there are nearly 6000 unemployed 
among those who lost their homes some people go around telling 
others that the us army is giving cash to every family and 
within minutes you have a mob asking for the money 
everybody is looking out for himself said miguel martinez 
23 we were not a very united community back in el chorrillo 
martinez was working as a helper in a home for the elderly next 
to el chorrillos church when the us effort to oust gen manuel 
antonio noriega began at 1230 am us officials say most of the 
damage wasnt caused by the attack itself but by fires set by 
noriega supporters 
we got everyone out safely the next morning martinez said 
the church did not burn down 
i guess i could go back but im trying to help here some of 
us get together and do volunteer work distributing medicines food 
cleaning up and doing other jobs we are here sharing the suffering 
of our brothers he said 
polio left manelis sanchez 19 without the use of his legs he 
was a popular figure in el chorrillo moving around on his crutches 
doing odd jobs or going to a busy corner downtown where he stopped 
cars and asked drivers for money for an operation 
he lived in a shack next to the church 
i was in bed when they started shooting he said my 
friend told me this is bushs christmas gift for noriega 
there are problems at the camp a security officer said there 
was some lowlevel drug selling and consumption 
remember a lot of the people in el chorillo lived off the sale 
and distribution of drugs and contraband said the officer who 
refused to give his name 
this week the us army stopped distributing ration packages to 
the refugees from now on food will have to come from private 
donations 
us soldiers still provide security but camp administration is 
being taken over by the panamanian red cross with help from the 
us agency for international development caritas a roman 
catholic charity and other charities 
it was a tough neighborhood they are boisterous complain 
about things want their own kind of food and are always arguing 
you have to understand them galvez said you must understand 
the trauma of an invasion the desperation of living in a refugee 
camp while others are discussing how long you are going to stay 
here and you hear them saying a year 
el chorrillo has been leveled and cleared by us army 
engineers most of the wooden threestory structures dating back to 
the beginning of the century are gone still standing are three 
concrete apartment buildings in need of extensive repairs 
estimates of the cost of rebuilding el chorrillo alone range 
from 30 million to 50 million the white house said thursday that 
it was earmarking 42 million in aid for housing emergency public 
works small business rehabilitation for looting victims and 
technical assistance to the government 
it is not certain congress will approve everything bush wants 
even though president guillermo endara said even 1 billion is only 
half what panama needs 
</TEXT>
