<TEXT>
president bushs 123 trillion federal budget 
for fiscal 1991 will contain a warning to congress from budget 
director richard g darman against seeking a wonderland in 
which military savings can be diverted to domestic programs 
administration officials said today 
the nearterm peace dividend is likely to be smaller than 
commonly assumed darman tells congress in an introduction to the 
budget document the officials said 
bushs budget plan will propose a reduction of the federal 
deficit to 631 billion roughly half as much as the current 
expected deficit through a series of austere military and domestic 
programs said the officials who spoke on the condition of 
anonymity 
bush will propose total spending of 1233 trillion and will 
project revenues to the government at 117 trillion 
the budget includes an austere 2921 billion for the pentagon 
which works out to a slight increase over current spending but a 
reduction of about 2 percent after inflation is taken into account 
the sources said 
some members of congress have proposed that the reductions in 
military tensions in eastern europe can be turned into a socalled 
peace dividend and spent on expanding social programs 
darman however will tell congress it would be naively 
euphoric to expect that the crumbling of the soviet empire will 
spell a final end to eastwest tensions 
in his preface to the budget to be formally submitted on 
monday darman will compare the federal budget to the ultimate 
cookie monster a reference to the character in the popular 
childrens television show sesame street the officials said 
speaking on the condition of anonymity 
its excess tendencies toward consumption are not exactly 
ennoblingbut at the same time its underlying motivation is 
clearly not malevolent what harm it might cause is largely 
unintended 
excerpts from darmans introduction first published in todays 
editions of the new york times were confirmed by administration 
officials 
darman also will tell congress that many programs in the budget 
are like pacman in the popular video game waiting to spring 
forward and consume another line of resources dots in the budget 
maze 
details of the budget were surfacing on friday in advance of the 
formal submission to congress 
bush himself tipped his hand on one major program increase 
announcing the proposal for the increase in spending on the head 
start program for lowincome children he said every youngster 
deserves the opportunity for a full and happy life 
bush said the new funds would permit head starts enrollment to 
grow to 667000 children or 70 percent of the nations 
disadvantaged fouryearolds currently it reaches 39 percent of 
eligible youths 
however the budget will also contain spending cuts and program 
slowdowns 
veterans will be among the victims of bushs proposed cutbacks 
sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity said the budget 
would require veterans to make down payments on va loans for the 
first time 4 percent on loans of over 25000 
larry w rivers executive director of the veterans of foreign 
wars called it an unreasonable proposal that dashes the 
dreams of countless veterans of participating in the american dream 
of home ownership 
bush who frequently says he wants to be remembered as the 
education president was proposing a 500 million overall 
increase in education spending but at the expense of some programs 
for instance the budget would reduce the guaranteed student 
loan program by 500 million sources said another 155 million 
would be cut from the perkins loan program for lowincome college 
students 
and although bush will call for longterm increases in pell 
grants another source of money for lowincome students his budget 
will reflect a cut in the grants by some 665 million for this 
coming fall as a result more than 13 students will either have 
their stipends reduced or eliminated the sources said 
overall its an inadequate investment said gerald morris 
deputy director of legislation for the american federation of 
teachers 
according to administration and congressional officials the 
budget will also include 
the most austere pentagon budget in more than a decade bush 
will propose 292 billion in new outlays up slightly from current 
spending but representing a 2 percent cut after adjusting for 
inflation however the budget will include a request for increased 
spending on the strategic defense initiative to 48 billion up 
from 38 billion this year 
more money for fish wildlife and recreation plus a cutback in 
federal timber sales 
a new family savings account that would allow people to 
earn taxfree interest and dividends on money that is squirreled 
away for at least seven years with contributions of up to 5000 
per year per family 
no new general tax hikes and a renewal of bushs call for a 
lower capital gains tax rate a tax credit for adoptions and one 
for child care 
a 85 billion slash in medicare funds 
bush has also announced that he will seek a 11 billion 
increase to 106 billion for the war on drugs 
some 24000 of the bluejacketed 1592page budget documents 
are being printed and they will go on sale on monday at government 
bookshops for 38 apiece 
but a new government economic report was already raising doubts 
about the administrations assertions that the bush budget would 
lower the federal deficit to 64 billion as required by the 
grammrudman budget balancing law 
the commerce department reported friday that economic growth in 
the last three months of 1989 fell to an annual rate of 05 percent 
when adjusted for inflation considerably worse than projected by 
the office of management and budget as it put together the economic 
assumptions for the new budget 
the economic figures will make total hash of the 
administrations claims that its spending outline can significantly 
reduce the budget deficit said michael evans president of a 
washingtonbased economic forecasting service 
</TEXT>
