<TEXT>
four men who were highranking 
officials in nicolae ceausescus regime went on trial saturday on 
charges they contributed to the deaths of hundreds of people during 
last months revolution 
one of the four former politburo member ion dinca told the 
court he was an accomplice to criminal measures ordered by 
ceausescu to try to crush the uprising 
dinca was the only one of the defendants called to testify 
during saturdays fourhour session but the prosecution presented 
declarations it said were from each of the defendants admitting 
their guilt 
on trial are former communist party secretary emil bobu former 
interior minister tudor postelnicu and former politburo members 
manea manescu and dinca 
they are charged with complicity in genocide in connection with 
the deaths of hundreds of people during the december revolution 
that ousted ceausescus government and face life in prison at hard 
labor if convicted 
the military prosecutor col aurel cosma said each man could 
have prevented the killings of at least 689 people shot to death by 
troops by asking ceausescu to resign instead they backed his 
order to shoot protesters cosma said before presenting the 
declarations purported to be from the accused 
cosma did not say when the declarations were given 
i was a beast because i agreed to the orders of nicolae 
ceausescu said a statement attributed to postelnicu 59 who 
partly controlled the securitate secret police i decided to 
fight alongside him until the end he said 
bobu considered the no 3 official in the government behind 
ceausescu and his wife elena was quoted as saying i didnt 
take a position my attitude was contemptible i was the one who 
suggested cremation of the victims in timisoara to hide evidence 
of the military action 
the revolt began in the western city of timisoara 
manescu 74 was quoted as saying i asked nicolae ceausescu 
not to resign i ordered fire with war munitions i agreed with the 
armys repression 
everyone with no exception proved to be cowards we carried 
out ceausescus orders said dinca 62 
hundreds of people crowded into a hall at the romanian military 
academy in bucharest to view the trial the first of former 
ceausescu associates since the dictator and his wife were tried in 
secret on genocide charges and executed christmas day 
the defendants entered the dock without handcuffs guarded by 
two armed policemen postelnicu appeared on the verge of tears 
prosecuting ceausescu loyalists is a key test of the provisional 
government which is struggling to gain the support of the people 
before free elections in may 
the trial opened one day after the vice president of the 
provisional government resigned claiming that stalinist 
methods were being used by the nations new leaders 
the charges referred to ceausescu and his wife as the 
authors of the genocide but said the four defendants did not 
act to block the ceausescus and therefore were guilty of complicity 
one of the issues raised at the session was of the events that 
led to security forces being ordered to open fire on demonstrators 
dinca in his testimony said he and four other politburo 
members opposed the presidents demand that they shoot at 
protesters and told ceausescu so at a politburo meeting dec 17 
it was the first time that ceausescu met with opposition from 
the politburo he said he got up from the council table very 
nervous and said will you please elect another general secretary 
if you dont agree with me 
dinca said some politburo members then gave their support to 
ceausescu who went ahead with the orders to shoot protesters 
i consider myself his accomplice in what he did dinca said 
if any of us had tried to oppose him others would have allied 
with us and we would have managed to convince him to give up such 
an order 
he added i didnt have the courage i didnt do it because of 
cowardice 
i gave my help to ceausescu to put into practice the criminal 
measures to suffocate in blood the justified revolution of the 
people he said 
the revolution was justified he said because romanians were 
deprived of basic human rights food medicine and energy to heat 
their homes 
ceausescu forced romanias 23 million people to endure 
hardships exporting food and energy supplies for heating as he 
sought to pay off romanias 10 billion foreign debt 
on dec 22 dinca said ceausescu called an emergency politburo 
meeting and asked if anyone objected to the steps he was taking to 
crush the revolt which by then had spread to bucharest and other 
cities 
everybody there said they would fight to the end dinca said 
by then defense minister vasile milea who had refused to shoot 
at protesters had himself been shot to death by proceausescu 
forces 
the ceausescus boarded a helicopter to flee bucharest on dec 
22 they were caught and executed christmas day after being 
convicted of genocide and ruining the economy the death penalty 
has since been outlawed 
under questioning from cosma dinca said milea told ceausescu on 
dec 17 that he had examined all the military regulations and 
didnt find anywhere that the armed forces should shoot the 
people 
before dinca finished testifying his three codefendants were 
asked if they had any questions for him manescu and bobu said no 
but postelnicu referring to shorthand transcripts of the 
politburo meetings said i think there are many lies in these 
papers 
the tribunal president col andrei nitoui said postelnicu 
could say more about that when he testifies 
nitoui adjourned the tribunal until monday 
