<DOCNO> AP900127-0116 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lewis mumford a critic of architecture and 
urban planning whose writings warned of the decline of cities and 
the dehumanizing influence of technology has died at age 94 
mumford who died in his sleep friday afternoon was frail 
but there was no sickness it was simply a matter of old age 
said his grandson james morss 
mumford best known for his writing on the subject of cities and 
culture was the author of more than 30 books including the city 
in history for which he received the national book award in 1961 
morss said his grandfather spent the last few years quietly 
passing the days with his wife and doing some light reading 
mumford was among 12 artists including composer aaron copland 
and film director frank capra awarded the national medal of arts 
by president reagan in a white house ceremony in 1986 recipients 
were honored for their lifetime contributions to american arts 
the illegitimate son of a businessman mumford was born in 
queens on oct 19 1895 but grew up on the west side of manhattan 
he attended city college but ill health prevented him from 
completing his degree instead he took graduate courses at 
columbia university and at the new school for social research 
it was then that he discovered the works of sir patrick geddes 
a scottish town planner whose influence he said was the most 
important one in his life 
after serving as a naval radio technician in world war i 
mumford became associate editor of the dial magazine his essays on 
housing and urban matters led him to become acting editor of the 
sociological review 
mumford cofounded the regional planning association of america 
in 1923 and served on the staff of the new york housing and 
regional planning commission 
in 1938 mumford published the culture of cities a book 
that traced the history of cities in the modern world and set forth 
proposals for their improvement the book made his international 
reputation and put him on the cover of time magazine 
he was among the earliest and most prescient critics of highways 
in manhattan in 1943 he wrote that express highways would be 
admirable if they were related to anything except the desire on 
the part of the more prosperous to get out of new york as fast as 
possible actually their function is to increase the planless 
decentralization of the metropolis and thereby pile up such a load 
of decaying properties in the center as to hasten the final 
exodus 
in addition to his writings on urban issues he wrote a weekly 
art column for the new yorker at the same time he published the 
first of four volumes in what became known as the renewal of 
life series 
a social philosopher and educator mumford implored people to 
place a higher value on human feelings and morals than on 
dehumanizing technology he feared that science and technology 
would eventually lead to a uniform allenveloping superplanetary 
structure designed for automatic operation 
man he said will then have not only conquered nature but 
detached himself as far as possible from organic habitat 
he is survived by his wife sophia daughter alison mumford 
morss of amenia and two grandchildren james of new york city 
and elizabeth of troy ny 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900127-0117 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bushs 123 trillion budget due to 
be unveiled monday will seek to slash the federal deficit in half 
in 1991 administration sources said saturday in a spending plan 
based on pareddown defense outlays and optimistic economic 
assumptions 
bush sticking to his campaign pledge will meet his deficit 
goal without a general tax increase opting instead to save 
billions of dollars through trimming a variety of government 
programs ranging from medicare to college student loans 
the budget document bushs first solo effort to reorder the 
governments spending priorities also will contain a somewhat 
whimsical overview written by budget director richard g darman 
who likens the federal budget to the ultimate cookie monster 
the voracious gremlin on the sesame street television program 
with a generally rosy set of assumptions about economic growth 
and with a host of proposed cuts in military and domestic spending 
programs the administration projects that the deficit for 1991 
will be reduced to 631 billion just under the 64 billion 
deficit target established in the grammrudman deficit reduction 
law 
the administration projects a deficit for the current fiscal 
year of 1238 billion far above the grammrudman target of 100 
billion according to officials who have seen the budget 
projections and who spoke on condition that their names not be used 
the budget forecasts the deficit will be reduced to 251 
billion in 1992 and will actually show a surplus of 57 billion in 
1993 the year the grammrudman law calls for a balanced budget it 
projects further surpluses of 107 billion in 1994 and 94 
billion in 1995 
former president ronald reagan also submitted budgets showing 
surpluses down the road but the surpluses never materialized 
because the economic assumptions upon which the revenue and 
spending forecasts were based proved too optimistic and congress 
balked at going along with many of the program cuts 
many analysts believe a similar fate will befall the 1991 bush 
budget the presidents first complete spending blueprint last 
february he released a 193page set of amendments to reagans 
final budget 
even before its release the bush administrations assumptions 
about economic growth were being called into question the 
congressional budget office projecting lower economic growth and 
thus lower government tax revenues is estimating higher deficits 
and thus the need for sharper cuts for 1991 and following years 
bushs 1991 budget for the fiscal year beginning next oct 1 
proposes total spending of 1233 trillion and expects government 
receipts will total 1170 trillion leaving a deficit of 631 
billion 
in his budget bush will propose using a portion of the surplus 
revenues in coming years to set up a social security integrity 
and debt reduction fund which would reduce the 28 trillion 
federal debt and thus leave a more manageable financing burden 
for future generations according to darmans overview 
the fund is the administrations effort to derail a politically 
popular proposal by sen daniel patrick moynihan dny to roll 
back social security tax increases this year and in 1992 
the budget does not include any proposed general tax increase 
continuing to honor bushs nonewtaxes campaign pledge to honor 
another 1988 pledge bush will once again seek to slash taxes on 
capital gains the profits resulting from the sale of stock or 
other assets that effort is certain to generate partisan wrangling 
on capitol hill 
to deflect arguments that the capital gains reduction is a tax 
cut for the wealthy bush will unveil a proposed family savings 
account which would allow people to earn taxfree interest and 
dividends on money invested for at least seven years with 
contributions of up to 5000 per year per family 
among the budget cuts bush will propose to trim 85 billion 
from projected spending on medicare the huge health plan for 
social security recipients the money would be saved by lowering 
payments to hospitals and doctors not by curbing patient benefits 
seeking to capitalize on the lowered eastwest tensions the 
administration is proposing a pareddown pentagon budget with 
outlays totaling 2921 billion up slightly from this year but 
representing a 2 percent cut after adjusting for inflation 
the 1991 budget proposes reducing active duty military personnel 
by 38000 cutting civilian defense department employment by 5000 
and reducing the reserves by 3000 while protecting some of 
administrations pet programs such as the strategic defense 
initiative the nuclear shield in space commonly called star wars 
by 1995 defense spending will be at its lowest level 
measured either as a share of the total economy or as a portion 
of total federal spending since before world war ii defense 
secretary richard cheney said in a pentagon budget document 
obtained by the associated press from congressional sources 
to help meet the trimmed down spending levels cheney is 
scheduled to unveil on monday a sweeping list of proposed military 
base closures and reductions over the next five years targeting 
installations from philadelphia to long beach calif 
cheneys moves have already prompted cries of protest from 
members of congress who have been briefed on which installations 
are on the hit list 
darman complains that congress has widely inflated expectations 
of how much in government resources will be freed up from the 
socalled peace dividend resulting from the reduced soviet threat 
in eastern europe 
this great historical shift has been almost trivialized in its 
translation into public debate about the budget the issue has been 
framed as how big is the peace dividend and in effect how 
can i get mine darman wrote in his essay first reported in 
saturdays new york times 
darmans colorful essay titled the directors introduction to 
the budget offers a tour of the budget wonderland with 
references to the budget as the ultimate cookie monster 
its excessive tendencies toward consumption are not exactly 
ennobling darman writes 
he also likens many huge government spending programs to the 
popular video game pac man as they wait to spring forward 
and consume another line of resource dots in the budget maze 
the 1592page bush budget bound with a blue cover will go on 
sale monday at government bookstores for 38 
</TEXT>
