<TEXT>
president bush hoping to derail support for a 
social security tax cut will offer as an alternative a proposal to 
use the growing social security surpluses to reduce the national 
debt administration officials said saturday 
the officials said the administration would spell out the 
workings of the proposal as part of bushs 1991 budget which will 
be released monday 
according to the officials who spoke on condition that their 
names not be used the debt reduction would work in the following 
way 
the budget will call for creation of a social security 
integrity and debt reduction fund to be administered by the 
treasury department 
the money for the fund would come from revenues collected by the 
government beginning in 1993 the year the administration projects 
the budget will finally enjoy a small surplus of 57 billion 
the bush proposal would call for the fund to receive an amount 
equal to 15 percent of the surplus that year in the social security 
trust fund the contribution would rise to 50 percent of the social 
security trust fund surplus in 1994 to 85 percent in 1995 and 
finally 100 percent from 1996 through the year 2000 
the congressional budget office estimates that the social 
security surplus the amount collected in payroll taxes above what 
is paid out in benefits will total 98 billion in 1993 rising to 
112 billion in 1994 and 128 billion in 1995 
the portion of the surplus funds flowing into the debt reduction 
account would be used to reduce the federal debt which now stands 
at 28 trillion 
by reducing the debt budget director richard g darman writes 
in a budget overview to be released monday policymakers would be 
leaving a more manageable financing burden for future 
generations 
the federal debt is the sum of all of the annual deficits since 
the government has not had a surplus for 30 years the treasury 
must add to the national debt by borrowing more each year 
the administrations plan assumes that the deficit reduction 
targets spelled out in the grammrudman law will be met and the 
government will start running surpluses in 1993 
however former president reagan also forecast surpluses in 
future years only to see those assumptions fail to occur because of 
slower economic growth and the unwillingness of congress to go 
along with his recommended cuts in domestic programs 
the administrations proposal for dealing with the social 
security surpluses is a recognition of the growing support for a 
proposal by sen daniel moynihan dny to reduce the social 
security tax paid by workers and their employers by 62 billion 
over the next two years 
moynihan wants to cut this years 765 percent social security 
payroll tax back to last years 751 percent rate and also cancel a 
further increase scheduled for next year 
bush has called the moynihan proposal a charade that could 
lead to an eventual reduction in social security benefits or force 
a general tax increase something the president has vowed to oppose 
moynihan has argued that the social security payroll tax should 
be reduced since the growing surpluses in the social security tax 
were not being saved to pay for the retirement of the baby boom 
generation but were instead being used to mask the governments 
real budget deficit 
