<TEXT>
blair bolles a former journalist who 
worked for the washington star and the blade of toledo and wrote a 
book about the reconstruction of europe after world war ii has 
died at age 78 
a cause of death was not immediately available he died friday 
bolles attended yale university and in 1935 began covering the 
white house and state department for the nowdefunct washington 
star 
he also wrote for a number of publications including the 
nation business week the new republic the st louis 
postdispatch click magazine and the king features syndicate 
his book the big change was based on his reporting for the 
blade from 1953 to 1956 and argued that europes old class 
structure would give way to a more consumeroriented americanized 
society 
bolles wrote three other books tyrant from illinois how 
to get rich in washington and men of good intentions in 
addition he coauthored americas chance of peace and a number 
of foreignpolicy booklets 
he began working for the blade in 1948 on a freelance basis 
providing foreign affairs analysis in 1953 bolles opened the 
newspapers paris bureau 
he returned to toledo in 1956 and worked as an associate editor 
at the blade until 1959 when he left toledo and began a business 
career with fairbanks whitney later known as colt industries he 
worked in the companys government affairs office in washington and 
retired in 1976 
bolles is survived by his sons harry devallon and blair jr 
a daughter zoe six grandchildren and a foster grandchild 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

