<TEXT>
the communist partys plan to dissolve 
itself and form a single new party with broader appeal was 
threatened saturday when a group of renegade members accused the 
leadership of making only cosmetic changes 
the communist party opened its final congress saturday to form a 
new party that it hopes will stand a better chance of winning power 
in an increasingly democratic poland 
after heated debate most delegates voted to suspend the congress 
of the polish united workers party the partys formal name and 
immediately open the founding congress of the new stillunnamed 
party 
but a leading progressive tadeusz fiszbach and about 100 
others refused to join saying no authentic reform had emerged and 
that the new party must shed part of its old conservative 
membership to draw support 
its not our goal to break up the party but we all are not 
going the same way fiszbach told about 200 delegates at a 
meeting early sunday after the congress recessed for the night 
fiszbach a communist parliamentary leader with backing from 
solidarity leader lech walesa was enlisting supporters for another 
new party to be called the social democratic union of the 
republic of poland 
communist leaders sought to negotiate with fiszbach in hopes of 
avoiding a split 
first secretary mieczyslaw f rakowski opened the threeday 
communist party congress with a surprise announcement that he would 
not try to lead a new party 
during the afternoon riot police clashed with hundreds of 
anticommunist demonstrators saturday outside congress hall no 
arrests or serious injuries were reported 
the agenda of the communist party congress called for dissolving 
the 41yearold party with a resounding condemnation of its 
ideology and endorsement of parliamentary democracy the starting 
work on the new party 
but the more than 1600 delegates voted overwhelmingly to change 
the order by proceeding with forming the new party before 
dissolving the old one 
fear about what would happen to the partys assets was a focal 
point of much of the debate over issues involved in the dissolution 
the legal status of buildings companies car fleets and other 
property amassed by the communist party during its long control is 
under review by a commission established last week the 
solidarityled government is trying to defuse public clamor to 
nationalize the communists holdings 
after the vote suspending the communist party congress 
delegates began signing cards making them founding members of the 
new still unnamed party which is likely to follow the social 
democratic model 
the delegates then quickly approved a 44member presidium for 
the new party and bylaws that had been prepared in advance 
but fiszbachs absence became public when his seat on a 
committee had to be reassigned 
he wanted immediate dissolution of the communist party and his 
backers said unless there was evidence of deep reform people would 
not believe a truly new party had been formed 
i havent seen manipulation of such a kind for a very very 
long time said communist parliament deputy wlodzimierz 
cimoszewicz 
mr rakowski should get a prize as the best magician of the 
year in one speech he turned communists into social democrats 
everything going on in that room is too good to be true 
rakowski and other leaders hope the new party will become the 
main leftwing party in polands widening democratic political 
spectrum 
the communist party ceded governing power to the solidarity 
movement after disastrous defeat last year in the freest elections 
here since world war ii 
poland since has plunged into economic reforms aimed at swiftly 
converting the system to free enterprise 
the nations communist party would become the second in the east 
bloc to reconstitute itself the hungarian socialist workers party 
transformed itself into the hungarian socialist party in october 
as delegates met more than 500 demonstrators from 
anticommunist groups gathered outside chanting communists must 
go they burned a red flag 
riot police moved in to push them away with a few police using 
truncheons one demonstrator was seen with a bloodied face 
the police moved the protesters a block away where 
demonstrators continued to hurl stones bottles firecrackers and a 
few gasoline bombs 
the delegates gathered in warsaws imposing stalinistera palace 
of culture and science where rakowski opened the meeting with a 
speech reviewing the partys past and discussing the future 
in announcing he would not seek a leadership role in a new 
party rakowski 65 said i consider it appropriate to pass over 
the helm to a new generation the delegates responded with a 
standing ovation 
rakowski appealed to the delegates whose opinions range from 
orthodox communism to extreme liberalism not to split into more 
than one party 
if we want to exist as a real force in the polish political 
scene we should not leave the congress hall through different 
exits he said 
rakowski said he had struggled to reform the party since the 
stalinist era ended in 1956 but failed because many members clung 
to stalinist ideas and the soviet union continued to interfere with 
polish reforms until the rise of mikhail s gorbachev in 1985 
referring to the past he said its true that we deserved a 
good whipping 
the party now claims 19 million members but the one that 
emerges after the congress will be much smaller politburo member 
janusz reykowski predicted in an interview 
walesa and the communist partys delegation in parliament have 
supported fiszbach to lead the new party fiszbach is a former 
gdansk party chief ousted from official positions in the 1980s 
because he opposed the 1981 imposition of martial law 
possible candidates include aleksander kwasniewski 35 now in 
charge of national sports and recreation or leszek miller 43 a 
party secretary and rakowski loyalist 
another potential candidate slawomir wiatr 37 founder of a 
liberal party faction on saturday announced his support for 
kwasniewski to be leader 
the communist party was founded in 1948 in a merger forced by 
soviet dictator josef stalin of the small communist polish workers 
party and the polish socialist party a leftwing party dating from 
the 19th century that enjoyed broad popular support 
now the party says it wants to give up the communist part of 
that heritage and become a social democratic group building on the 
old socialist tradition 
